,"Papillary necrosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPost-renal acute kidney injury occurs due to obstruction of urinary flow anywhere from the renal tubules to the urethral meatus. Causes can be classified as functional (potentially reversible) or structural (anatomical).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurogenic bladder\u003C/strong\u003E is a functional cause resulting from impaired neural control of bladder emptying, which can occur in conditions like spinal cord injury or multiple sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe structural causes listed include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUreteric stones\u003C/strong\u003E - mechanical obstruction within the ureter\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetroperitoneal fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E - external compression of the ureters\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProstatic hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E - mechanical obstruction at the bladder outlet\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPapillary necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E - structural damage to the renal papillae causing obstruction within the collecting system\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFunctional causes are potentially reversible with appropriate treatment of the underlying condition, while structural causes often require surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Post-renal acute kidney injury occurs due to urinary tract obstruction, which can be functional (reversible) or structural (anatomical)","Neurogenic bladder is a functional cause of urinary obstruction due to impaired neural control of bladder emptying","Common structural causes of urinary obstruction include stones, prostatic hyperplasia, and external compression"],"references":["Turgut F, Awad AS, Abdel-Rahman EM. Acute Kidney Injury: Medical Causes and Pathogenesis. J Clin Med. 2023 Jan 3;12(1):375. doi: 10.3390/jcm12010375. PMID: 36615175; PMCID: PMC9821234.","Truzzi JC, de Almeida FG, Sacomani CA, Reis J, Rocha FET. Neurogenic bladder - concepts and treatment recommendations. Int Braz J Urol. 2022 Mar-Apr;48(2):220-243. doi: 10.1590/S1677-5538.IBJU.2021.0098. PMID: 34156189; PMCID: PMC8932021.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53031"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15055"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53031"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T19:27:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T19:27:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7743"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67579"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Leve